Alerts
---------
alerts=> we need to take action now

==>Understanding Aggregation in Alerts
Alerts use TWO aggregations:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Time aggregation
2Ô∏è‚É£ Space aggregation


1.TIME Aggregation
Example:
avg(last_5m):metric
Means:
Take last 5 minutes of data and average it.

2.SPACE Aggregation
Example:
avg:system.cpu.user{env:prod}
Means:
Average across all hosts.
example:
If:
Host1 = 95%
Host2 = 20%
Host3 = 25%

avg = 46%
No alert.

But if you use:
max:system.cpu.user{env:prod}
max = 95%
======================================================

Important Alert Decision
Ask:
Do I care about cluster health or single host?
Cluster health ‚Üí avg
Single host safety ‚Üí max by host

What is Aggregation?
When you create an alert in Datadog, system asks:
How do you want to combine data?
There are two directions:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Across hosts (space aggregation)
2Ô∏è‚É£ Across time (time aggregation)
================================================

First Understand: What is Aggregation?

Aggregation = ‚ÄúHow Datadog combines data‚Äù

There are 2 types in alerts:

Type	                     Meaning	                                        Think Like
Time Aggregation	         How values are combined over time	Over            minutes
Space Aggregation	         How values are combined across machines	          Across instances


Example:
Time aggregation =
‚ÄúHow metric values are combined over a time window?‚Äù
Example:
Last 5 minutes
Last 10 minutes
Last 15 minutes

=======================
2Ô∏è‚É£ What is Space Aggregation? (Across Hosts)
üëâ Simple Meaning:
How to combine multiple instances / hosts
Example: 3 EC2 instances CPU at same time:

Instance	CPU
i-1	40%
i-2	60%
i-3	90%

Now Datadog must combine these.
That combining = Space Aggregation


if we use max() if we have 5 isnatnce any one ec2 instance  reach 80% we get alerts






